text: More lying crap from hollywierd.The civil war was not fought over slavery!  In 1900, there was an historical investigation into the Newt Knight affair.  The investigation found that Knight and several others deserted the  Confederate army and returned to their homes in Jones County,  Mississippi. Hiding out in the Leaf River swamps, Knight and his men  made raids, especially on trains. While Knight and his men attempted to  join with Union forces they were unable to do so because both yankee and  rebel viewed the deserters as an enemy. At no time was there any  attempt to separate Jones County from the rest of the state of  Mississippi or the Confederacy.  The term "Free State Of Jones" originated during the early 1830s. It was because so many people in the county had moved to other parts of the state that Jones county became almost depopulated.  Also, the majority of Jones Countians supported the Confederacy, even if they had initially opposed secession. Beware of what Hollywood tells you is a true story in history.  Caveat Emptor!

text: In 1894 J. L. M. Curry, a Southern educator, sounded the alarm, warning Southerners of the dangers of allowing their children to be taught from Northern textbooks. He declared that, if Southerners continued the practice, future generations would grow up to be ashamed of their Southern heritage. In 1930 Frank L. Owsley again warned the Southern people that the North was attempting to imprint its views upon the minds of Southern youth. He warned that the North was attempting to teach Southern young people that their history was a history of error. He warned of textbooks designed to give Southerners a proper education in Northern traditions and at the same time label the Southern cause as evil or unrighteous. As Owsley pointed out, the North made every attempt to destroy the South with naked military force. After the war came the second attack. The North, by using its control of the newly created national government, labeled the Southern cause as evil, slave-based, and racist: while at the same time, it claimed for itself the invader, the role of champion of morality, freedom and equality.

We get this distorted image of all confederate soldiers being evil white guys who were fighting solely for the issue of Slavery and nothing else. What is not pointed out is that many minorities fought on the side of and joined the Confederacy and fought against the Union. Some of these minorities include individuals of ethnic backgrounds: Jews, Latinos, Filipinos, Native Americans... Not to mention that the average Confederate solider (white or minority) were poor farmers who didn't have slaves. They simply fought for what they believed to be the preservation of their home soil.  I like how this movie addresses an issue that the benefactors of this war on the Southern side were big plantation owners and not all Southerners were evil in this misunderstood war.

The ghastly manacles are highlighted and the camera pauses on a sight of a lynching long enough to dissuade any viewer from any laconic view of a disgraceful reminder of outright White on Black terrorist activity. The hatred as (expressed in lynchings), the suppression of the vote, the income inequality are cautionary tales of what our current president, Donald Trump can and is visiting upon the United States today. ‚ÄìJV. text: Newt Knight was a coward. My great (x3) grandfather and his brothers served in the same unit (the 7th Mississippi Battalion), and they hated him for what he and his "followers" did while they were away in the war. While all responsible, able-bodied men were away fighting those invaders in north Mississippi, Newt and those other cowards preyed on defenseless women and children in Jones Country, only to run and hide in Eastabuchie Swamp whenever any adult men were present. He was not an officer, and he deserted before the 7th ever saw any action against the Union (at Corinth). If anyone thinks the inhabitants of Jones Country supported him, then why do you think they erected that massive memorial  (still standing today) to the Confederate Soldiers of Jones County on the courthouse grounds in Ellisville (rhetorical question). The coward isn't even buried in Jones Country, as his family knew no cemetery in the area of Soso (six miles from our ancestral farm) would accept his remains. That movie is absolute fiction, like so much coming from that bastion of political correctness in Hollywood.
